nomy. Culinary Colonialism, Caribbean Cookbooks, and Recipes for National Independence integrates new documents into the Caribbean archive and presents them in a rare pan-Caribbean perspective. The first book-length consideration of Caribbean cookbooks, Culinary Colonialism joins a growing body of work in Caribbean studies and food studies that considers the intersections of food writing, race, class, gender, and nationality. A selection of recipes, culled from the archive that Culinary Colonialism assembles, allows readers to savor the confluence of culinary traditions and local specifications that connect and distinguish national cuisines in the Caribbean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCaribbean Area-History-Autonomy and independence movements. 0aCookbookszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aCookbooks-Caribbean Area-History. 0aCookingxPolitical aspectszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aCooking-Political aspects-Caribbean Area-History. 0aFood writingxPolitical aspectszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aFood writing-Political aspects-Caribbean Area-History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  afood, food studies, caribbean, culture, customs, traditions, independence, national identity, colonialism, cookbooks, cultural studies, race.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079131040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882957240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978829572423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978829572/original  a978-3-11-079131-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles